review_content: an exciting movie filled with plenty of action, adventure, beautiful cinematography and best of all, terrific performances..Ledger is fantastic as Kelly

Cinematic and wonderful on the big screen, this magnificent remake revisits the grandeur of the western, tossing around elements of morality in the melee of good pitted against evil... Russell Crowe is splendid.

movie_title: Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid
review_content: Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969) is the likeably entertaining, charming and amusing comedy/drama of the friendship and camaraderie shared between the two handsome and humorous buddy leads - legendary, turn-of-the-century Western outlaws...

As a western it's enthralling with depth and visual splendour, resonating like sunstroke, but the film soon unfurls into a terror-fired juggernaut that macerates the senses then leaves you amazed, exhilarated and hugely entertained.

Like many esteemed classics of the genre, Bone Tomahawk is an exploitation movie at heart, but has the courage of its convictions to treat its material as a gory grindhouse feature, albeit one made with love and effort.
All great farces need a certain insane focus, an intensity that declares how important they are to themselves. This movie is too confident, too relaxed, too clever to be really funny.
Engaging and enjoyable, this is an impressively directed, beautifully shot Western with a thoughtful script and terrific performances from Sam Shepard and Eduardo Noriega.
It's an exciting movie filled with plenty of action, adventure, beautiful cinematography and best of all, terrific performances.
This is not one of Howard's better films, but a mediocre Ron Howard film is better than the best of better than half of Hollywood.

movie_title: The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford
review_content: Awesome splendor and a striking essay on celebrity reward those who brave the 2 1/2-hour run time.
Quality entertainment. There's lot of action, thrills, adventure and some great landscape...The performances are great

movie_title: The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford
review_content: The running time and pacing may scare some, but Dominik has crafted an instant classic, with poetic visuals, sensational performances and a true love for the genre. Magnificent.
Those old values of family, loyalty and bravery don't get trotted out much anymore.... The film does them justice, and provides stimulating movie fare along the way.
It is certainly one of the best westerns ever made, and the best film of any kind to come out in 1969.
The film is pretty much a standard Western. It is also, like most of its kind, a pleasant means of passing an hour and a half in air-conditioned comfort.
With one of the greatest opening sequences in film history, High Noon kicks-off in an outstanding fashion and this 1952 film just gets better and better as it builds towards its climax.
Entertains the way a summer matinee movie should, with an agreeable blend of romance, action, humor, and a likeable cast.

Over-long, often clichd and uneven (there are comic interludes complete with cameo performances), but still imbued with moments of true poetry, thanks largely to William Clothier's magnificent Panavision landscapes.
Not just one of this year's best films, but also one my favorite westerns ever...What an entertaining, thoughtful, relevant film this is.

movie_title: A Million Ways to Die in the West
review_content: The jokes are mostly funny, the songs are charming, the scatology is only occasionally off-putting and overall it's a pretty good time at ye ol' air-conditioned nickelodeon.
The script of Three Amigos plays like it was slapped together by a few friends with a tape recorder enjoying a charming weekend at the beach.

Harris's adoration for the genre is clear, and his Appaloosa is a fine addition to a growing list of neo-westerns incorporating a respectful tone, ideal aim of violence, and heartfelt observation all in the same breath.
It's incredibly inconsequential, buttery entertainment, but it'll surely put a smile on your face if you can find a way to appreciate its rambunctious spirit.

movie_title: A Million Ways to Die in the West
review_content: The script squanders many opportunities for real laughs and it continually plays it safe with sophomoric humor that would create giggles in middle-schoolers.
With its stunning Flagstaff, Arizona locations and a breezy tone, the John Wayne-produced "Angel and the Badman" is a delightful mix of romance and action, with excellent chemistry between the leads.
A grittily entertaining and thoughtful example of just how good a western can be..an outlaw tale that is at once exciting and elegiac, elegant and earthy.

movie_title: The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford
review_content: Beautifully directed, visually stunning Western with terrific performances from Casey Affleck and Brad Pitt - this is one of the best films of the year.

movie_title: Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid
review_content: The John Foreman production is episodic, but George Roy Hill's direction is so satisfying in catching the full value of the Goldman screenplay that a high degree of interest is sustained.

It's way too early to signal the rebirth of the western at the movies, but if it happens, it'll be because of smart and thoughtful entertainment like this that sucks audiences in whether or not they care how the West was won.

While overlong and awfully leisurely (as well as remarkably gory)...quite enjoyable, rather like a version of 'The Hills Have Eyes' transplanted to the old West and enriched by a strong cast and a good deal of flavorful, if often digressive, dialogue.

movie_title: The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford
review_content: Stunning visuals, award-worthy performances, and a script that takes incredibly rewarding risks, Jesse James is a masterpiece and one of the best films of the year.
The presence of two great actors already puts a few points in the win column, and 3:10 to Yuma rolls along efficiently like a wagon with finely tuned wheels.

movie_title: The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford
review_content: The slow pace and the fact that the title gives away the entire plot should only be a minor annoyance to those who love strong writing, powerful acting and great filmmaking.

movie_title: A Million Ways to Die in the West
review_content: At the end of the day, no matter how poorly this may be directed, written, and acted, the only thing a good comedy needs to do is make you laugh and this one does it in spades. Funniest comedy of 2014.

However, gore aside the humour's wonderfully thick and dark like molasses will have you chuckling throughout. The characters are well drawn including the female character which is a welcome trend in modern westerns.
A gentle, warmly human and quietly compelling western with a wry sense of humour and some engaging performances from a group of fine actors.

An excellent Western. Jerome Morris' score is one of the all-time greats, standing in the company of Elmer Bernstein's The Magnificent Seven theme and Ennio Morricone's Spaghetti Western contributions as the genre's best.

A fine dramatic comedy with fresh characters, witty dialogue and a keen interest in how relationships must have developed among frontier folks, tyrannical ranchers, no-nonsense lawmen and -- oh, yes -- the complicated women on that frontier.
Vastly entertaining in the old-fashioned ways: fun story, fun characters, fun everything.
Much better than this year's Open Range, and just as good as the award winning (and in my opinion overrated) Unforgiven.

I give thanks for westerns. Every time they seem to be about to gasp their last, dusty breath, one comes along to give them a bit of renewed life. Bless it, the western genre will not die. Last year it was the excellent remake 3:10 to Yuma. This ye
Cate Blanchett embodies the strong, complex, capable heroine, delivering a richly detailed, Oscar-caliber performance...

There's no true grit to be found in James Mangold's fun but safe Western remake. Nitpicking, however, is no way to treat a movie that gives us two heavyweights like Russell Crowe and Christian Bale on top of their games.
This is a fine, mature work: adult, intelligent and moral, creating a laconic new persona for the admirable Stewart.

A handsome production that pays great attention to authentic representation of the era, the legend and the landscape, Ned Kelly excels visually as it recounts a story that many may not fully know, albeit limiting our emotional connection with the man.

movie_title: An American Tail - Fievel Goes West
review_content: Primarily aimed at children, it is a cartoon romp with the honky-tonk humor of a Looney Tunes adventure. But it is witty, well crafted-and clever enough to amuse adults.

movie_title: The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford
review_content: Of all the many films about Jesse James, Andrew Dominik's epic may not end up ranking as the most popular or the best film on the subject but it will certainly, flaws and all, be regarded as the most intriguing and ambitious take on the man and his myth.

It's a wonderful surprise to discover that this new version, starring Russell Crowe and Christian Bale and directed by James Mangold, not only remains true to its roots but expands on them in ways that are thrilling and thoroughly entertaining.
It is among the best films of the nineties and the best independent features ever made in the United States.

Viggo Mortensen's brilliantly cool performance engenders enough good will to see "Appaloosa" through its pokey meandering to an intriguingly philosophical conclusion: a look at modern outsourcing, capitalism and progress through a Western prism.
a pleasant surprise, especially for what is basically a DVD release... and it helps to have two gorgeous women headlining the film
Kudos to director James Mangold for not letting anything stand in the way of splendid performances in this impressive remake.
The performances by Shepard and Rea make this a movie worth seeing--as does the opportunity to visually drink in the seldom-seen beauty and stark magnificence of Bolivia's high country.
...something fresh and mature and honest by dint of superior treatment all along the line.

Burl Ives won the Supporting Actor Oscar for playing a patriarch in William Wyler's sprawling, overlong Western, though the award also might have been given to him for similar part in Cat on Hot Tin Roof.
The Magnificent Seven emerges as not only ludicrously enjoyable entertainment but also a superior and thoughtful character study.

The best Western since Unforgiven, 3:10 to Yuma is both cathartic and intelligent. While a wildly eventful action-adventure and outlaw shoot-'em-up, it's also a vibrant story of heroism, villainy and hard-earned redemption.
The minutes tick toward 3:10, and all we can do is watch and hope that it all turns out ok. That's the best kind of Western, one that allows feelings like that to emerge while watching.

Worth seeing for its Western-genre pleasures and for its truly awesome Bolivian locations, which function almost as a rebuke to those special-effects-oriented filmmakers who prefer green screen to our green planet.

The iconoclastic, not-politically-correct Blazing Saddles (1974) is one of Mel Brooks' funniest, most successful and most popular films. It is an unsubtle spoof or parody of all the cliches from the time-honored genre of westerns...

movie_title: A Million Ways to Die in the West
review_content: [McFarlane] is trying to push boundaries that most politically correct comedies and comedians stampeded away from years ago. For me, that is how the West is truly won.
Yes, Outlaws follows a template, but it does so expertly and at such a lively pace that its familiarity becomes a pleasure in itself for a knowing audience.

movie_title: A Million Ways to Die in the West
review_content: It's another example of MacFarlane's ability to mix poop jokes with romance, foul language with sweet sentiment, offensive humor with boyish charm.
One of Wayne's top B efforts; an offbeat love story that works as a romance as well as a Western. Russell is luminous.
Those who have a deeper abiding love for the western genre than I, may love the new Yuma. I liked a good deal of it -- just enough to be frustrated by the clutter.
Armed with his Beautiful Mind Oscar, Ron Howard stretches his wings with this attempt at a dark, wholly adult western. I just wish it was a more successful one.

Revolving around two very different but equally impressive performances from its leads, James Mangold's remake is everything you want from a western: stunning vistas, gripping shoot-outs and a morally complex core that is compelling to the end.
At last! A feature film about Australia's greatest outlaw and folk hero that, while not reaching five-star status, all Australians can be proud of.
The close confines of cinematographer Phedon Papamichael's camera, coupled with brilliant dialogue delivered by great actors on top of their game, allow us to overlook the letdown of a finale.
It's a smart, creepy, violent, funny, and modern vampire movie that benefits from some wonderful performances, a stunning visual texture, and music by Tangerine Dream.
One of the most popular Westerns of all time, the heroic story of The Magnificent Seven has influenced countless other movies in nearly every genre.
An enjoyable western that's an excellent reminder of how - in the world of movies - sometimes less is best.
Zahler's commitment to objective realism, despite his out-there premise, denies the audience the sort of engagement that might have made Bone Tomahawk truly subversive, and truly great.
Blazing Saddles is not for everyone -- but there are great pleasures here for anyone willing to seek them out.
I love a good western, so I am not very enamored with Appaloosa. I guess you can say I just want to be friends with it.
Director Scott Stewart has fun with the genre, making effective use of 3D technology and amid the ridiculous, delivers an often surprisingly compelling B-movie with some superior elements.
As happens with big-screen comics, the dialogue fizzles at times. But mostly this is a delicious mash-up of styles and genres: gothic, steampunk, Wild West, martial arts, dystopian fun.
At its best, Brimstone is like being caught up in one of God's more entertaining divine rages.
Hollywood's great revisionist western, well deserving of its Best Picture Oscar
Wow! What a grueling, richly rewarding and meticulously crafted film.

Lone Star, one of Sayles best and most popular films, explores the historical strain between the Mexican and American communities in Texas. Though a bit didactic (too many sermons), it's well acted and visually more satisfying than his other films

movie_title: Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid
review_content: It is a great film and will be an exceptionally popular and profitable one.
One of the truly great Westerns, directed and acted with flawless skill in the old style.
A terrific movie with excellent performances from Crowe and Bale. If it doesn't find itself on the short list of Academy Award contenders, the film itself has been robbed.

movie_title: The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford
review_content: Above all, there's the sense of immersion in a world of harsh beauty whose time is running out. It's to be hoped that non-American audiences embrace this film: it's one of the year's very best.
It shouldn't be missed by anyone with a taste for Eastwood's typically slanted morality. It's the actor/director's best movie -- and the best Western by anybody -- in over 20 years.
It's a history lesson that's made entertaining because so many of the performances are so powerful and heartfelt.
... let it be said loud and clear: In almost every respect, Mangold's new version is superior to the original.
Eastwood's meditation on age, repute, courage, heroism -- on all those burdens he has been carrying with such good grace for decades.

movie_title: Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid
review_content: A cool, charming, anachronistic Western, with great chemistry between Newman and Redford, that reimagines the genre for youths of the era by turning the outlaws into mythic figures.
One of the best vampire movies ever made....if you liked "The Lost Boys", you'll love this!

The two leads' sparking byplay, Crowe's addled cockiness versus Bale's nervy grit, would grace any surroundings, but it's a pleasure to revisit the frontier in a drama which feels far more vital than mere nostalgic homage.

movie_title: The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford
review_content: This is a 160-minute art Western, and if you're up for such a beast it is a glory to behold. It's gorgeous, but rarely for the sake of mere gorgeousness, and languorous, but never listless.
If there ever were an award for best modern vampire flick, this would certainly be in the running for first place.
Sayles has surrounded his hero with other, more interesting characters and has warmed Lone Star with the glow of a humanist optimism rare in contemporary movies.

movie_title: A Million Ways to Die in the West
review_content: While it does suffer from the old syndrome of most of the funny parts being in the trailer, there are still plenty of funny jokes that weren't. Unfortunately, there still aren't enough funny jokes to fill the movie's runtime.
Hardly a fresh perspective on genre traditions, it's still got the performances and glorious landscapes to win you over.
Powerful and provocative, The Missing is another masterful production from one of the industry's best directors and two of its best actors.
The dreamiest Jesse James ever, looking less like a bandit and more like the grand prize in my sister's old 'Mystery Date' board game.
These days elegiac Westerns are the only kind anyone seems interested in making anymore. But when the result is a film as moody and beautiful as Mateo Gil's Blackthorn, that's not a bad thing at all.
A wannabe Western epic that never quite fills the widescreen, but is quite lovely around the fringes. A bit like Australia.
Brooks' wholehearted embracing of rank vulgarity, together with his innovative quickfire sketch structure, titillated crowds more used to sophisticated Hollywood humour.
Blackthorn is a handsomely mounted film, with many an awesome vista and rolling plain, but compared to the quicksilver brilliance of its predecessors, it comes off as irredeemably minor.
It honors both the genre and the original film without doing harm to either while containing enough of its own virtues to allow it to stand alone as its own entity.
This is a fine, handsomely staged movie, as exciting and stimulating as anything I've seen this year.
A handsome and skillful retelling of a legend that imaginatively draws on conventions of both the western and the gangster movie to create an energetic yet thoughtful contemporary action-adventure.

Great cinematography takes more than plopping a camera down in a desert canyon ... though it helps. It takes John Wayne framed by a doorway. Gary Cooper's walk. Clint Eastwood's squint. Gene Hackman's grin. And, now, Russell Crowe's eyes.
Beautifully shot and impressively directed, it's an ambitious Western in the classic mold, the kind of film that rarely gets made anymore.
Engaging, well made Western with exciting action sequences, a thought-provoking script and terrific performances from Bale and Crowe.
S Craig Zahler's strikingly confident and richly imagined debut feature is a film that deserves to be discovered and celebrated.
True, the film is a little long, and it loses momentum at one stage, but generally speaking this is a most enjoyable return to what was once the cinema's most popular genre.

Made in the vein of The Gunfighter and High Noon, this mature psychological Western is arguably Delmer Daves best film, featuring Van Heflin (in the Gary Cooper role) and Glenn Ford as the bad-good guy at their most appealing and accomplished.
Crowe and Bale are a great study in contrasts, yet the two characters develop a grudging respect for each other that enriches the murky morality play that makes up the last half hour.
Meaningful in its implications, as well as loaded with interest and suspense, High Noon is a western to challenge Stagecoach for the all-time championship.
The plot is engaging enough but this is best viewed as a buddy movie with a dynamite duo at its core.
Not only one of the year's biggest and best surprises, but it's the most beautifully photographed film I've seen in some considerable time.
I'm not sure how dumb it was supposed to be, but laughing at it -- if not with it -- is a good enough way to spend 94 minutes.
"Cimarron" is magnificent in scope, powerful in treatment, admirable in acting. But it is even more than all this. It is one of few talking picture productions which inspires rather than awes.
The result is impressive: a handsome, intelligent cavalry western.

movie_title: A Million Ways to Die in the West
review_content: MacFarlane's comedic approach has always been that of throw everything at the wall and see what sticks. It's no different this time out, and the jokes are so plentiful that the odds are in this movie's favor for a substantial number of them to succeed.
Clint Eastwood's 1992 western Unforgiven earned the director his first Oscars, for Best Picture and Best Director.
A large measure of their success is due to an accomplished screenplay by Waldo Salt-pungent, racy, and with a nice line in over the shoulder throwaways.
Gene Hackman and Clint Eastwood face off in one of the best westerns ever made -- make that the best western ever made -- produced some 50 years after the prime of the western era.
Exciting, looks great, and even with the heavy emphasis on gunplay and action, it's well acted, especially by Christian Bale.

Enjoy it for the handsome wide-screen vistas, the interplay of the actors, the classical sweep of its story line. Just don't expect the new, soul-searching Eastwood to be any more dramatically convincing than the old.
More intellectually rewarding than emotionally satisfying.
There may be debates about Yordan's Oscar-winning script, but Dmytryk's direction of this compelling Western is taut and the acting, especially by Tracy and Katy Jurado (Oscar-nominated), is superb.

movie_title: The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford
review_content: It's Dominik's uncompromising, uncommercial vision and the two leads that give the story such a wonderfully wounded grandeur.
The Wild Bunch is an American masterpiece, one of the greatest films ever produced in the Hollywood system.
Though this Western is interesting and artistically daring, it's far too brutal and sadistic (and far too long) to recommend for casual viewing; it requires strong resolve and a stomach to match.
As a pistol-packin' cowgirl in fringed leather trousers, Day is terrific, an object of athletic awe and irrepressible good cheer.
A terrific turn by Peter Fonda, as a leathery bounty hunter hell-bent on retribution, is a bonus in a film far livelier than anyone had a right to expect.

movie_title: The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford
review_content: Casey Affleck gives an outstanding performance that proves him to be a character actor of immense creativity, clarity and composure.

It's exciting, thrilling, romantic, and thoroughly entertaining.. And it's all anchored by a rousing performance from Douglas Fairbanks. This is what going to the movies should be about: Pure escapism!
Witty, beautifully shot and genuinely terrifying, this is an extremely impressive and thoroughly enjoyable horror-western. Future cult status seems assured.
Pays homage to the classic Western by staying true to genre conventions, but does so with a fresh set of eyes that gives the film a welcome place in a modern multiplex.

movie_title: A Million Ways to Die in the West
review_content: A Million Ways to Die in the West is guaranteed to divide audiences, but it's a really solid comedy with more than enough laughs to offset its minor shortcomings.
A terrific, old-fashioned western, proof positive that sometimes, they do "make 'em like they used to."
This is a spectacular western away from all others. It holds action, sentiment, sympathy, thrills and comedy -- and 100% clean.

On the list of things the world needs, a mash-up of The Searchers and Hannibal is pretty far down there. But if there is going to be such a thing, the smartly cast and well-crafted Bone Tomahawk fills the bill nicely.
Buoyed by a strong cast and carried by an interesting mix of genre sensibilities, it's a film that may not have much lasting value but is fun nonetheless.
A historically credible but overly prosaic account of the most celebrated episode in the creation of an Americanized Texas.
Peckinpah shows atypical humor and sense of music too in this original and lyrical comedy-Western-musical, with Jason Robards in top form as one of the director's most sympathetic character.
The action's fairly toothless, and the abrupt, anemic ending promises a sequel. The filmmakers will have to pray pretty hard for that miracle.
One of the best westerns from the 1950s - a decade replete with magnificent westerns.
Howard's overambitious film manages to cast a spell, even in those stretches when it's easier to admire than it is to enjoy.

movie_title: Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid
review_content: The film is a raffish, good humored ballad with Butch and Sundance as a pair of lovable rogues -- a Bonnie and Clyde to a ragtime beat.
The heart-stopping, breathtaking journey of 3:10 to Yuma reminds us just how exciting a good, old-fashioned movie can be.
The Missing is holiday entertainment for anyone who likes either a dollop of feminist uplift or family values (or both!) with their bloodletting.
A film that can stand proudly in the rarefied company of the very best westerns ever made.
About the best you can say about Mangold's work is that it won't kill off the genre. Nor will it help to revive it.
The opening sequence of this wonderful musical is pure pleasure, as Doris Day rides the Deadwood stage across the screen and into our hearts.
The requisite standoffs and shootouts make this one tense film, but the mood is frequently lightened with a generous dose of surprising humor.

No thrill comes cheap in Unforgiven. The West that it shows is Wild all right, but more like a dog than a party. That doesn't mean we can't enjoy being dragged along for the ride; the rougher the better, in fact, as every action zings with ricochets.
The first western to win an Oscar for Best Picture.
Let's cast a lot of cute boys as the James/Younger gang. In between hold-ups, they can bicker about who's the cutest and, oh yeah, they can take their shirts off a lot.
Westerns may be old fashioned, but as old-school homages go, superb writing and compelling acting will never go out of style.
Madeline Kahn was nominated for the Supporting Actress Oscar for her wonderful parody of all the cabaret singers that Dietrich used to play, including the comedy-Western Destry Rides Again.
High Noon (1952) is possibly the all-time best Western film ever made - a successful box-office production by Stanley Kramer
This is neither Fonda's finest role nor a very challenging one - it's a cleavage and one-liner affair - but it's fun and entertaining.
Zahlers dialogue takes us effortlessly back to the Old West, the cast are excellent, and a few stumbles aside this is best campfire movie for some time.
A warmly made, slightly offbeat movie about friendly devotion. It also happens to be a western, and every man in it is grizzled or wizened or both.
Beautifully photographed by Dean Semler, Appaloosa is the best Western since Open Range and shows there's still life in this most unfashionable of genres.

It is one of those incredible, intensely cinematic journeys, where everything from panoramic to infinitesimal, from fording a river to creeping thorough undergrowth is visually exciting and where excitement and sympathy go together.
Three Amigos is likable, but it never really finds a distinctive style. Not quite parody and not quite serious, it's more like a lengthy costume party.
old-fashioned but simple and effective entertainment
In an era where monster mythology has become raw material for all sorts of mediocrity, Priest is one of the best examples of a broad-scale vampire blockbuster.
A respectable and at times an exciting film that should appeal to males of all ages, history buffs and -- yes, it's inevitable -- patriots.
A great cast is eclipsed by the hilarious performances of Harvey Korman and Madeline Kahn, who plays a Marlene Dietrich-like chanteuse.

movie_title: Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid
review_content: Although Butch Cassidy wasn't the first movie to pair up a couple of wisecracking best friends in an action/adventure setting, this film became the model of how well that approach could work when done right.

Crackling eccentric verbal wit as Harris' marshal seeks to 'button up this town tighter than a nun's corset' while overcome by Zellweger's irresistible flirty charms, because she 'chews her food nicely and even takes a bath before going to bed.
3:10 to Yuma manages to incorporate the rhythms of a contemporary action movie while maintaining a healthy respect for the tenets of the genre. That makes it a train well worth catching.
The great, stirring epic "Lone Star" stands as a peak in the career of John Sayles, who already has such admirably serious films to his credit.

movie_title: A Million Ways to Die in the West
review_content: Demolishes the heroic mystique of the Old West with the nose-thumbing glee of a rambunctious brat who has just crawled out of a fetid mud puddle.
A splendid reinvention of the 1957 movie alternating vivid gunfights against a gorgeous background with brain-games of the most manipulative sort.

movie_title: Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid
review_content: It's still fun, but was it ever a great film?
fine production values and an Oscar nomination worthy performance from Billy Bob Thornton make The Alamo worthwhile
The greatest enjoyment in watching Stagecoach is in observing how Ford builds and populates this moral universe, in seeing complex personalities sketched in simple words or gestures.

Though handsome to look at (cinematography is by Owen Roizman), the movie is overlong, stately, and too detailed for its own good; director Kasdan claims his version if more accurate, which may be true, but it doesn't make for a good picture.

Elevated above the usual fare by an engaging and complex relationship between its two stars, 3:10 To Yuma would be a thoroughly entertaining two hours whatever the genre - the Western setting is almost a bonus.

It's not hard to view "The Ballad of Little Jo" as an allegorical critique of sex and power and men's-club values in America. In its disdain for those values, the film is as focused and cool-headed as the remarkable character whose story it tells.

A smart and funny script, highly entertaining from the first draw, Appaloosa is a taut, captivating tale of the old West with enough bite and modern edge to draw in both fans and non-devotees of the cowboy genre.

The rugged background of Monument Valley, Ariz..., the admirable pace given to the screen play by Writer Dudley Nichols and Director John Ford, the unostentatious acting of a well-chosen cast make it one of the season's most satisfactory pictures.
It's nowhere near as funny as it should have been given the talent on show, but the chemistry between the stars and the gentle digs at the western genre make for a diverting enough entertainment.

Each frame is a crystalline jaw-dropper that places the smallish actions of men within a vast canvas of lush jungle, lunar salt flats, Andean snow, and desert sand. The result is a pretty good movie that almost looks better than it needs to.
If you're someone who orders the usual and is just happy when it comes out warm and fresh, I reckon Appaloosa will sit with you just fine.
Despite a twist at the end and some striking scenery, this revival suggests that some legends are best left in peace.
Classic John Wayne Western masterpiece promotes tolerance.
With its great acting, great pacing, and crackerjack storyline, Yuma is not only fun, it is surprisingly moral.
The songs are catchy and fun (well sung by Doris Day). It's a great movie!
It's never a bad time for a good western and Bone Tomahawk is a good western...
If you enjoy brainless slapstick that allows space for irrelvant absurdities like a singing bush and an invisible swordsman, it's entertaining enough.
The film is sometimes too gabby and too sentimental but is magnificent to look at, and the inexorable climax is awesome in its scope and fury.
[Director James] Mangold has been smart or fortunate in casting, and personalities sustain interest even when the narrative flags.

Peckinpah tells intense tales of male bonding, where honor and loyalty are the codes to follow, even if it means a bloody end. When paired with the mythology of the Western, it adds up to a fascinating movie.
A sort of futuristic fantasy western with 'The Searchers' as its granddad, 'Priest' is an action adventure that will attract fans of the graphic novel and folks who like fantasy in general.
Director John Sturges was extremely fortunate in securing a near-perfect cast for this enduringly popular western reworking of Japanese classic Seven Samurai.

It is impossible, of course, in a short notice to give any real idea of so full and detailed a picture -- but Cimarron is emphatically a film which everyone looking for a good entertainment should see.
There's no point in wondering whether 3:10 to Yuma will trigger another revival of the genre. But for two exciting hours, the picture brings it fully alive once again.

movie_title: A Million Ways to Die in the West
review_content: Despite all of the obvious flaws, I did find myself caught up thanks to MacFarlane and Theron's chemistry, and there were just enough genuine laughs to keep me entertained.
An unforgettable, powerful Western of unequaled quality that boasts one of the greatest of all movie endings.

One of the best Westerns ever made, Ford's Stagecoach is a very stylized work, shot in black-and-white and influenced by German Expressionism. Sharply written by Dudley Nichols, it features strong characterizations well-played by the entire ensemble.

Much as late 19th century Australian outlaw Ned Kelly was a charismatic figure who won the adulation of the Irish immigrant masses there, Heath Ledger as that romantic revolutionary of the film's title breathes astonishing vigor into the role.

What gives Zahler's brutal, bloody, and just plain bizarre film a lot of its oomph is the dialogue, by turns lyrical, absurd, odd, and inventive.
Silly, insipid and, most tragically, dishonest and revisionist.
Exhausting, pretentious, and tedious. It's one of the most painfully boring, overlong and disappointing Westerns since Heaven's Gate.
A grim portrayal of unremitting brutality against women exacerbated by perverted religious belief, whose extraordinary stylishness doesn't entirely compensate for its underlying unpleasantness.

movie_title: A Million Ways to Die in the West
review_content: There's not much that's good in it, plenty that's bad, and an awful lot that's just plain ugly.
Drab, eye-rollingly stupid and with noisy effects designed to drown out audience snores, Priest is just about as bad as it gets.

movie_title: The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford
review_content: The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford is the story...of the moment in America when myth was murdered by mere celebrity and we were left, perhaps forever, with only the latter's meager consolations.

movie_title: A Million Ways to Die in the West
review_content: Stupefying in its unfunniness, arrogance and outright narcissism, A Million Ways to Die in the West is a shoo-in for my Worst of the Year list come December.

A mlange of apocalyptic western, gothic horror and vampire action movie, Priest won't win any awards for originality. Still, it's streamlined and executed well enough to earn a tip of the cap from those in its target demo.

movie_title: A Million Ways to Die in the West
review_content: If MacFarlane was going for comedic shock value with this film, he failed miserably. What he has put on screen in 2014 is no longer funny or shocking, just stupid and a bit sick.
For my money, Bone Tomahawk isn't just the best horror movie of 2015, it's the best movie, full stop.

This is a deep, brooding western rooted in frailty and retribution. There is depravity in this tale of kidnapping, murder and sexual exploitation that cannot be easily dismissed or explained, a collection of woe and pain will not be put to rest.
A mash-up of vampire horror and period westerns stewed with Blade Runner cityscapes and ridiculous religious images in a bubbling cauldron of dumb ideas and sinfully bad dialogue.
The scenes of the bullying are long and violent and bloody and boring.
For all the visceral depictions of hatred and violence and human destruction, it feels as if the director is chasing his own tail and forgetting about making it all mean something.
Ostentatiously unpleasant, mired in a grim solemnity nowhere near as intelligent nor enlightening as the film seems to think it is.
[A] tastefully packaged but borderline offensive slice of revenge porn, which starts promisingly but is slowly (alas, very slowly) drowned by backstory.
It's a somber feature, but one of extraordinary character development, bundled into a compelling story of men facing their sins in a most brutal, pitiless manner.

The Missing has to be one of the more brutal, repulsive and doggedly unpleasant Westerns ever made by a major studio -- so grim and depressing it's hard to imagine how anyone but a masochistic critic could stand to sit through it.
Those timeless New Mexico backdrops may lend the production its desired authenticity, but all those structural wide-open spaces stop "Big Kill" dead in its tedious tracks.
Women never have a great time in Westerns, but Brimstone takes it to extremes; inflicting endless humiliation, misery and trauma upon its female characters.
The Missing is well made, suspenseful, and superlatively acted for the most part, but its harshness never feels organic to the tale. What should be devastating is just terribly unpleasant.
